## Finding: `crime_00052` — Duplicate Component Shape

Same form-footer `<div>` subtree (Cancel link + submit Button, wrapped in `mt-6 flex justify-end gap-4`) is hand-rolled in 4 invoice forms. Only the submit label varies between create (`"Create Invoice"`) and edit (`"Edit Invoice"`). The Cancel link's `href` and styling are identical across all four.

### Files that would change

Extract a new shared component:

- `dashboard/final-example/app/ui/invoices/form-actions.tsx` *(new)*
- `dashboard/starter-example/app/ui/invoices/form-actions.tsx` *(new)*

Call sites that lose their inline footer `<div>`:

- `dashboard/final-example/app/ui/invoices/create-form.tsx` (lines 142–150)
- `dashboard/final-example/app/ui/invoices/edit-form.tsx` (lines 152–160)
- `dashboard/starter-example/app/ui/invoices/create-form.tsx` (lines 101–109)
- `dashboard/starter-example/app/ui/invoices/edit-form.tsx` (lines 112–120)

(Two new files because `final-example` and `starter-example` are independent Next.js apps in the fixture — they don't share a package. If they did, this would collapse to one file under a shared `ui/` package.)

### Shared component API

```tsx
// app/ui/invoices/form-actions.tsx
import Link from 'next/link';
import { Button } from '@/app/ui/button';
import type { ReactNode } from 'react';

export type InvoiceFormActionsProps = {
  /** Where Cancel routes back to. Defaults to the invoices index. */
  cancelHref?: string;
  /** Label on the submit button — the only thing that varies today
      ("Create Invoice" vs "Edit Invoice"). */
  submitLabel: ReactNode;
  /** Override Cancel's label if a future form needs "Discard" etc. */
  cancelLabel?: ReactNode;
  /** Disable submit during pending server-action state. */
  pending?: boolean;
};

export function InvoiceFormActions({
  cancelHref = '/dashboard/invoices',
  submitLabel,
  cancelLabel = 'Cancel',
  pending = false,
}: InvoiceFormActionsProps) {
  return (
    <div className="mt-6 flex justify-end gap-4">
      <Link
        href={cancelHref}
        className="flex h-10 items-center rounded-lg bg-gray-100 px-4 text-sm font-medium text-gray-600 transition-colors hover:bg-gray-200"
      >
        {cancelLabel}
      </Link>
      <Button type="submit" aria-disabled={pending}>
        {submitLabel}
      </Button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Props rationale (only what the evidence justifies):**

| Prop | Required | Why it exists |
|---|---|---|
| `submitLabel` | yes | The single observed variation point across the 4 sites. |
| `cancelHref` | no, defaults to `/dashboard/invoices` | All 4 sites use the same href today; defaulting keeps existing call sites to one prop. |
| `cancelLabel` | no, defaults to `'Cancel'` | Not varied today, but cheap optionality for the next form (delete/duplicate) — and lets the label match the action verb. |
| `pending` | no | Forward-looking for `useFormStatus()` / server-action submission states. Omit if you want to stay strict to "extract what's there." |

**Slots (children-style escape hatches):** intentionally none. The subtree is a 2-element action row with a stable visual contract — adding a `children` slot would invite call sites to drift the shape again, which is exactly what the finding is flagging. If a future form needs a third button (e.g. "Save draft"), add a named `extraActions?: ReactNode` slot *then*, not preemptively.

**Call-site shape after refactor:**

```tsx
// create-form.tsx
<InvoiceFormActions submitLabel="Create Invoice" />

// edit-form.tsx
<InvoiceFormActions submitLabel="Edit Invoice" />
```

### Risk notes

- `final-example/edit-form.tsx:148` uses `my-2` for the error `<p>`, vs `mt-2` in `create-form.tsx:138` — that's a *separate* drift inside the sibling `aria-live` block and is **not** part of this finding (different subtree). Worth noting because an agent doing this refactor will see it adjacent and may be tempted to "fix" it; don't expand scope.
- This refactor only touches presentational JSX; no behavior change, no test changes required. Confidence on the finding is 0.7, agent_risk 0.57 — medium-risk extraction because the four files share intent today but live in independent apps, so the duplication may be deliberate fixture isolation rather than accidental drift.
